    <name>
      <text>Mathematical computations using reciprocals</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3 style="text-align:center;">Solve the following using reciprocals</h3>


<ol type="a">
<li>\( {@a_num@} \div \frac{{@a_den@}}{{@a_num@}} \)</li>
<li>\( {@b_coeff@}x = {@b_rhs@} \)</li>
<li>\( \frac{{@c_num@}}{{@c_den@}} x = {@c_rhs@} \)</li>
<li>\( {@dec1@} \div {@dec2@} \)</li>
</ol>


<p>
(a) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]<br>
(b) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]<br>
(c) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]<br>
(d) [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]
</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked solution</h3>
<p>Dividing by a number is the same as multiplying by its reciprocal.</p>


<ol type="i">
<li>First, replace division by multiplication with the reciprocal.</li>
<li>Then simplify the expression.</li>
<li>Finding the value of\(x\) is like dividing the value after the equal sign by the reciprocal of the coefficient of \(x\) </li>
</ol>


<ol type="a">
<li>\( {@a_num@} \div \frac{{@a_den@}}{{@a_num@}} = {@a_num@} \times  \frac{{@a_num@}}{{@a_den@}}\) <br>
\(= {@ta_a@}\).<br>
</li>
<li>To find the value of \(x\) in \( {@b_coeff@}x = {@b_rhs@} \), first find the reciprocal of the \(x\) co-efficient then multiply it by the value after the equal sign. <br>
\(x= \frac{1}{ {@b_coeff@}} \times  {@b_rhs@}\)<br>
Therefore,  \(x = {@ta_b@}\).<br></li>
<li>Finding \(x\) in \( \frac{{@c_num@}}{{@c_den@}} x = {@c_rhs@} \), we have:<br>
 \(x = \frac{{@c_den@}}{{@c_num@}} \times  {@c_rhs@} \)<br>         
Hence, \(x = {@ta_c@}\).</li>
<li>\( {@dec1@} \div {@dec2@}  = \frac{{@d1@}}{{@10@}} \div  \frac{{@d2@}}{{@10@}}\)<br>
   \( = \frac{{@d1@}}{{@10@}} \times \frac{{@10@}}{{@d2@}}\)   
<br> \(= {@ta_d@}\)</li>
</ol>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
